 Jergensen  ,   Jergenson  ,   Jorgenson  , and   Yorgensen  ."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Cecilia Jorgenson was born in 1256, in Ayrshire, Scotland as the daughter of Ronson Jorgenson. She married Reginald Crawford about 1268, in Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1310, in Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1256–1310":"1256–1310","1253–1297":"1253–1297","1269–1307":"1269–1307","1274–1319":"1274–1319","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1280–1360":"1280–1360","1224–1342":"1224–1342","1275":"1275","1297":"1297","1253":"1253","1274":"1274","1360":"1360","1280":"1280","13 February 1307":"13. veebruar 1307","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1256":"1256","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","about 1268":"umbes 1268","1319":"1319","1307":"1307","about 1274":"umbes 1274","Auchenames, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Carlisle, E